### The Structure
Every `if` statement must close with `fi` (`if` spelled backward).

```bash
#!/bin/bash

if [ condition ]
then
    echo "Condition is TRUE"
elif [ another_condition ]
then
    echo "First condition is FALSE, but this one is TRUE"
else
    echo "All conditions are FALSE"
fi

[!NOTE]You can also write if [ condition ]; then on a single line. The semicolon ; acts as a newline indicator.Bash uses letter-based flags for comparing numbers inside single brackets [ ].FlagMeaningMathematical Equivalent-eqEqual to=-neNot equal to!=-gtGreater than>-geGreater than or equal to>=-ltLess than<-leLess than or equal to<=

#!/bin/bash

AGE=18

if [ "$AGE" -ge 18 ]; then
    echo "✅ Success: You are eligible to vote."
else
    echo "❌ Access Denied: You must be 18 or older."
fi

When working with text, standard operators are used.OperatorMeaning= or ==Strings are identical!=Strings are completely different-zString is Empty (Zero length)-nString is Not Empty

#!/bin/bash

USERNAME="admin"

if [ -z "$USERNAME" ]; then
    echo "⚠️ Warning: Username cannot be blank."
elif [ "$USERNAME" == "admin" ]; then
    echo "🔓 Welcome, Administrator."
else
    echo "👤 Welcome, Guest User."
fi

Essential operations for DevOps and System Administration workflows to verify files or folders before running operations.FlagMeaning-eObject exists (can be a file OR a folder)-fExists and is explicitly a regular file-dExists and is explicitly a directory (folder)-rFile has read permissions granted-wFile has write permissions granted-xFile is executable

#!/bin/bash

LOG_FILE="/var/log/system.log"

if [ -f "$LOG_FILE" ]; then
    echo "📂 File found. Reading system entries..."
elif [ -d "$LOG_FILE" ]; then
    echo "⚠️ Target path is a directory, not a file."
else
    echo "🚨 Critical: Log file missing. Initializing new log..."
    touch "$LOG_FILE"
fi

To test multiple conditions at once, use advanced double brackets [[ ... ]] (Recommended for modern Bash).

Modern Standard: [[ ... ]]
&& : AND (Both conditions must pass)

|| : OR (At least one condition must pass)

! : NOT (Inverts the true/false status)

#!/bin/bash

HOUR=14
DAY="Saturday"

# Using OR (||)
if [[ "$DAY" == "Saturday" || "$DAY" == "Sunday" ]]; then
    echo "🏖️ It's the weekend! No automated builds today."
fi

# Using AND (&&)
if [[ "$HOUR" -ge 9 && "$HOUR" -le 17 ]]; then
    echo "💼 System checking is restricted during business hours."
fi

Legacy Old-School Standard: [ ... ]
If parsing plain legacy POSIX /bin/sh scripts, use flag parameters:

-a : AND

-o : OR


# Old school equivalents:
if [ "$HOUR" -ge 9 -a "$HOUR" -le 17 ]

[!TIP]
Recommendation: Stick to [[ ... ]] with && and ||. It prevents syntax bugs with empty strings and handles variables safer.

